          <td valign="top">

<span class="txth1">HiColors : Colorscheme display and editor</span> 

<br>
<br>

<!-- karma table -->
<table cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" border="1" bordercolor="#000066">
<tr>
  <td class="lightbg"><b>&nbsp;script karma&nbsp;</b></td>
  <td>
    Rating <b>41/18</b>,
    Downloaded by 2074  </td>
  <td class="lightbg">
  <b>&nbsp;Comments, bugs, improvements&nbsp;</b>
  </td>
  <td>
    <a href="http://vim.wikia.com/wiki/Script:1081">Vim wiki</a>
  </td>  
</tr>
</table>
<p>

<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0">
<tr><td class="prompt">created by</td></tr>
<tr><td><a href="/account/profile.php?user_id=96">Charles Campbell</a></td></tr>
<tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="prompt">script type</td></tr>
<tr><td>syntax</td></tr>
<tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="prompt">description</td></tr>
<tr><td>You'll get to see your colornames' colors and edit your colorscheme with the hicolors ftplugin/syntax/help files.&nbsp;&nbsp;Leftclick on any colorname and you'll bring up the help page on that colorname (if any).<br><br>To see an example, click on<br><br>	<a target="_blank" href="http://mysite.verizon.net/astronaut/vim/colors/hicolors.html">http://mysite.verizon.net/astronaut/vim/colors/hicolors.html</A><br><br>to see hicolors displaying the astronaut colorscheme (<a href="/scripts/script.php?script_id=122">vimscript#122</a>) color selections for the various highlighting groups.<br><br>This script is auto-installable via GetLatestVimScripts, too (<a href="/scripts/script.php?script_id=642">vimscript#642</a>).<br><br>Use it with <a href="/scripts/script.php?script_id=625">vimscript#625</a> (colorscheme sampler) to see what highlighting groups are supported and what the colors will be.<br><br>Bring up the colorscheme editor on each color by right-clicking on the color's name.&nbsp;&nbsp;Use the mouse's left button to click and drag on the colorbars to select and change colors.&nbsp;&nbsp;It works with both the gui and those console vims which support the mouse!&nbsp;&nbsp;You can then write the colorscheme (you'll be prompted for a filename), cancel the change, or indicate that the change is done for that colorname.<br><br>----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>USAGE<br><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;:help hicolors<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;leftmouse&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;on a colorname to bring up help on that colorname<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;rightmouse&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp; on a colorname to bring up the colorscheme editor for that color<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;leftmouse&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;click&drag on any colorbar to change the color for that colorname<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;leftmouse&gt;&nbsp;&nbsp;to select WriteColorscheme, Cancel, or Done<br><br>----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br><br>(alpha/beta version available at <a target="_blank" href="http://mysite.verizon.net/astronaut/vim/index.html#HICOLORS">http://mysite.verizon.net/astronaut/vim/index.html#HICOLORS</A>)<br></td></tr>
<tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr>
<tr><td class="prompt">install details</td></tr>
<tr><td>hicolors is now distributed as a vimball!&nbsp;&nbsp;(see :help vimball)<br><br>vim hicolors.vba.gz<br>:so %<br>:q<br><br>For windows users who aren't using a cygwin/gcc compiled vim:<br>vim -u NONE -N syntax\hicolors.vim<br>:set ff=dos<br>:wq<br>vim -u NONE -N doc\hicolors.txt<br>:set ff=dos<br>:wq<br>vim -u NONE -N ftplugin\hicolors.vim<br>:set ff=dos<br>:wq</td></tr>
<tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr>
</table>

